<DOC><DOCNO> AP880902-0099 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1024EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w PM-DrunkenDriving     09-02 0223</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Drunken Driving,220</SECOND><HEAD>MADD Focusing on Drunken Driving This Weekend</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mothers Against Drunk Driving and otherorganizations will focus attention this weekend on efforts to enddrunken driving with national advertisements, local events and arequest that motorists turn on their headlights, officialsannounced today.   Representatives of MADD, federal, state and local governmentsand Volkswagen United States Inc. asked Americans to promise to notdrink and drive on Saturday and to show support for the ``Drive forLife'' program by driving with their headlights on.   ``We're asking all Americans to make this pledge with the hopethat they will continue their commitment never to drink anddrive,'' Norma Phillips, national president of MADD, told a newsconference.   Last year, 23,632 Americans were killed and 560,000 were injuredin accidents attributed to drunken driving, according to MADD. Onlast year's Drive for Life day, the traffic fatality rate dropped28 percent, MADD says.   ``We must constantly remind the American people of thesestatistics, and do all we can to mobilize them to stop thecarnage,'' said Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley.   Under a congressional resolution signed by President Reagan,this weekend has been proclaimed National Drive for Life Weekend.Over the long Labor Day weekend, the rate of fatal accidents causedby drunken driving usually increases by 10 percent, MADD says.</TEXT></DOC>